Editor's Note: This is Jiaqiu's last isolation (see here and here) . Originally he said it was possible to go to Hubei as soon as the quarantine was over, so this was interesting. I said, "better not, health first, " and I thought to myself, "I know. "

In the end, Katsura's isolation ended peacefully. He's still in Beijing, but based on what I've read about him over the past few weeks (here and here) , it's only a matter of time before he takes another adventure. Keep him safe. Keep him safe. And looking forward to his next story.

Fireworks, March. Quarantine expired.

Nearly 20 years of voice gathering of more than a dozen old classmates on-line, after the warm greetings, they settled down to the common memory of SARS in 2003: At that time, only the blue days of reading, and do not know the taste of youth.

Humans are optimistic, forgetful creatures, yes.

A spring rain, all things recovery, upstairs from the neighbors of the long-lost quarrel. In the mail, bills, rent, wages, and tickets keep popping up. The deals were due to expire, and the calls were unsolicited.

Time to pick up where we left off? Telecommuting and learning are the new normal. Even my friends in Hubei began to tell me that I was no longer nervous and even numb to the daily figures. Those who do not want to mention the memory, followed the rain, carrying the virus into the earth.

Residents in the district go out to practice Taijiquan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Neighborhood Committee, which hasn't let up in the slightest, has taken me off the priority list.

But I still did not formally out of the house, in addition to the same home-based work, perhaps because there are still some things not willing to do?

Back to the year of SARS: Before the campus was officially closed, the teacher gave the students a choice, the result of living in west Beijing, I am not isolated in the East Street No. 1. The only surprise was that at the end of the semester I produced a dozen of my best report cards in four years.

This time, the isolation felt the same: the constant stream of distractions, the paucity of choices, the hours that forced me to focus.

Pictures from my friends'circle

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A hundred years ago in the dark hours of mankind, there was room for a quiet desk after all. Today, in the days of mass isolation, the daily fast-paced life of reading, writing, cooking, flower arrangement, calligraphy and painting, tea ceremony and health care and other national customs, I have been in the circle of friends and myself for a long time to review.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When a senior documentary filmmaker heard me coughing up phlegm and wheezing on the phone, he not only immediately sent me the MOXA stick, but also included notes from famous ancient doctors such as Sun Simiao.

In addition to the headlines and the controversial practice of traditional Chinese medicine in this outbreak, our forefathers also practiced the practice of "isolation" -- from the Qin Dynasty onward, in the book of Jin, it is written, "the Ason family sometimes had diseases, and those who infected more than three people were not ill and could not enter the palace for 100 days. " Isn't it just that today's incubation period is isolated from "intimate contact" ?

Emperor Xuanzong of Tang attached great importance to information disclosure, carved the quarantine and treatment of the epidemic on wooden boards all over the country; Munjong wrote letters during the epidemic to reduce household taxes; and both the Sui Dynasty special for leprosy patients, "Lilianfang" , or the Tang Dynasty "eminent monk biography" in the "to receive illness, men and women do not Fang, four-time supply, Order Zhou to give" configuration, than the fire mountain isolation hospital, more like today's shelter.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taoyuan Wonderland, Qiu Ying

The leprosy that has plagued the Chinese nation for thousands of years reminds me of my days in Daliang Mountain, Sichuan, after 2008: a few days later, I came down in the face of huge numbers of desperately poor, HIV / aids-ravaged, hollowed-out villages in Yi people, the team felt the numbness and despair of the villagers, and the group was almost overwhelmed by the situation.

It would take three or four hours to get back to the county seat, and the car drove cautiously down the deserted mountain road, overlooking the rushing waters of the deep stream. Suddenly, we saw a shabby old suspension bridge, old and out of place. A local NGO representative leading the team said the suspension bridge was the only way in and out of the village of leprosy, which has been carved out of the ground since the 1950s, deep in the lonely mountain opposite the bridge.

In fact, leprosy in China has long been truly "preventable, controllable and treatable, " but left a large number of people with leprosy disabilities. They still live on an island more remote than the badlands and are forgotten.

At our entreaties, the leader finally led us across the drawbridge and walked for two hours until we met the brothers and sisters on the steep slope and found the entrance to the village.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The elder sister helps the younger brother who breaks the foot to walk back leprosy village, Qiu Jiaqiu to photograph

The Small Square at the entrance to the village was filled with old people chatting and playing Mah Jongg, middle aged men and women slash-and-burn and weaving on the ground, and the hilltop classrooms, close to the Blue Sky, as if for a few days before, i have just witnessed the plight of the entire village of 300 school-age children out of school.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"cured" leper, photo by Qiu Jiaqiu

Four generations of lepers, mutilated but not broken. Watching them laugh with hope, even representatives of local ngos are aghast. From the risk of death decades ago to flee, to today's migrant villagers secretly fled to settle down in Leper village. This isolated island, although still poor, but we are not familiar with the performance of life.

My good friend Heffen said to me today: The US has ended the war in Afghanistan, the conflict between Syria and Turkey has escalated, millions of people have been displaced, Turkey has opened its borders, tens of thousands of Syrian refugees have stormed the barrier and are planning to flee to Europe, was supposed to be the big story of the day. These are also human suffering, and have shattered countless happy families. For the injured, their home is the heart of the epidemic and the whole tragedy.

How much darkness is there in the shadow of the epidemic? The night before last, I received a message on Wechat:

"I've always found it difficult to set up a training base and have been lied to over and over again, and I've run up debts, but I don't feel bad about it. I can slowly pay back the epidemic. A month has passed, and now I don't know what to do. I've been watching a lot of armless people these days, and they've been posting a lot of videos, for attention, for life, and I've been having a hard time with that, but now I'm thinking a lot, and I want to sell myself for the sake of the organization."

This is from the armless Harvard -- one of the most positive, optimistic, and self reliant people I have ever met. For a decade, her organization has been training people with disabilities of all kinds -- deaf, deaf, down's, autistic, physically disabled -- to work and reintegrate them into society.

"every time you move in Beijing, " she told me, "you think there might not be a disabled person living in this neighborhood. " Once settled down, the swallow went out for a morning walk.

"Half a month later, I was walking along a path when a disabled man came up to me and nodded shyly. The next day, another handicapped guy walks up to me and waves. Slowly, I found that there were many disabled people living in the community, just like the ones I had lived in."They saw swallows, and out of their closed homes.

In fact, many people have been in the eyes of the public, isolated themselves, in our side. Now, the man who helped them out of their invisible isolation is himself at a crossroads.

The quarantine will expire, and disaster will come again and again. What else did we leave behind before it was over?

A month ago, we helped coordinate medical supplies from around the world to support the hard-hit region of Wenzhou, Zhejiang. Now, with the global outbreak of new coronavirus pneumonia, the Wenzhou residents association has begun to reverse itself and provide full support to the hard-hit areas overseas. "Due to the severity of the outbreak in Italy, we decided to send the goods to Milan, Italy first. "

The epidemic of the century is upon us, and no one is safe from it. Isn't the "community of human destiny" supposed to be so much more cohesive than the still-anti-china sentiment, racism and talk of "cutting off foreign imports" ? Leper village turned its borders upside down, apparently not by suspicion under a mask.

The old man selling vegetables, as mentioned before, had a falling out with his family because he insisted on taking risks late at night to deliver affordable vegetables to his clients. However, at the critical moment of resuming work during the busiest farming season, he not only received material support from the vegetable farmers, several brothers and sisters in the Family Group also rushed to the home to help.

"I'm the luckiest one, I have brothers and sisters, I have brothers and sisters, I have a third in the middle, I don't have to worry about anything. "

Later I learned that the old man was the top student in the middle school entrance examination when he was young. He gave up the chance to go to university and stayed in his hometown to work in agriculture. But he never gave up his literary talent, his dream and his integrity.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Qing River discharge map (Zhu Ying in "Kyushu Traveler" is based on ancient lepers who were forcibly quarantined and lived by discharge; the book is about isolation, disability, dignity and the unknown) 

Those who once had a dream, despite their life, burn themselves, even if only for a retrograde, a short way.

In the early morning, swallow Standing Tall on the neighborhood's footpath, the stubborn old man shuttling along the familiar village path, the river flowing under the suspension bridge that connects the island and the hearts of the people.

Life is hard, life is always hard.

Quarantine noted
